Why “full greedy” sounds appealing

A greedy approach (always choosing the move with the lowest immediate cost) is great because it:

Minimizes rotations for each individual push
Keeps operations locally optimal

So it works very well when:

Stack B → A (reinsertion phase), where order matters a lot
Where it breaks down (A → B)

If you also go greedy when pushing A → B, you run into problems:

You lose structure in B
Elements get pushed in a chaotic order
Later, greedy reinsertion becomes more expensive because:
You can’t exploit partial ordering
You need more rotations to fix B

👉 In other words: greedy early → chaos later

Why chunking (or grouping) is still useful

Chunking during A → B gives you:

A semi-sorted B (usually descending or layered)
Predictable positions for reinsertion
Fewer total operations overall

You’re trading:

Slightly more cost upfront
for
Much cheaper reconstruction
Best-performing hybrid strategy

