Good choice—chunk + greedy is where most high-scoring push_swap solutions live. But it only works well if a few key details are done right. Miss these, and your move count explodes.

I’ll give you the must-know concepts, not fluff.

🔑 1. Normalize your values (VERY important)

Before anything:

Map all numbers to their index in the sorted array
So values become 0 → n-1

Example:

[-5, 100, 2] → [0, 2, 1]

✅ Why:

Chunking becomes trivial (ranges of indices)
Comparisons are faster and cleaner
🔑 2. Chunk definition (don’t overcomplicate it)

Use:

chunk_size ≈ 1.5–2 * sqrt(n)

Then:

chunk = [i, i + chunk_size)

You iterate chunks from smallest → largest.

🔑 3. The A → B phase (THIS is where most people mess up)

Goal: build a structured B, not just push numbers.

Core rule:

When pushing from A to B:

If value is in current chunk → pb
Then:
If it's in lower half of chunk → rb
If it's in upper half → don’t rotate
Why this works

You’re building B like this:

Top → bigger values
Bottom → smaller values

So B becomes roughly descending

👉 This makes greedy reinsertion MUCH cheaper

Extra optimization (important)

When searching for next element in chunk:

Check if it's closer from top or bottom of A
Use:
ra if closer to top
rra if closer to bottom

❗ This alone can save thousands of moves

🔑 4. Don’t strictly finish chunks

This is subtle but important:

👉 You don’t need to perfectly empty each chunk before moving on

Instead:

Work in a sliding window
Accept values slightly outside strict bounds

This reduces excessive rotations.

🔑 5. Greedy phase (B → A) — THIS is the core

For each element in B, compute:

Cost:
cost = moves_in_A + moves_in_B

Where:

moves_in_A = rotations to place it correctly in A
moves_in_B = rotations to bring it to top of B
You must handle 4 cases:
ra + rb
rra + rrb
ra + rrb
rra + rb

And optimize:

Use rr when both rotate up
Use rrr when both rotate down

👉 This is where top implementations win

🔑 6. Insert position in A (CRITICAL)

For a value x from B:

Find where it fits in A such that:

prev < x < next

Edge case:

If x is min or max → place after max

👉 If you get this wrong, everything breaks

🔑 7. Always pick the CHEAPEST move

Loop through all elements in B:

Compute total cost
Pick the minimum
Execute it

👉 Never just take the top of B blindly

🔑 8. Final alignment

At the end:

Rotate A so smallest value is on top

Use:

ra or rra depending on position
⚠️ Common mistakes (these kill performance)
❌ Not normalizing values
❌ Not rotating B during push phase
❌ Ignoring reverse rotations (rrr)
❌ Reinserting in wrong position in A
❌ Not choosing cheapest element from B
❌ Using fixed chunk size for all n
🧠 Mental model
A → B: organize data (chunking, shaping B)
B → A: exploit structure (greedy optimization)

If B is messy → greedy becomes expensive
If B is structured → greedy becomes insanely efficient

